column1: Contents: UCR Index arrest and offense data for the 90 largest counties, for 1990-1996
Source files: National Archive of Criminal Justice Data,  (http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/NACJD/)
FBI Uniform Crime Reporting Program Data [United States]: County-Level Detailed Arrest and Offense Data
to refer questions about this file or  for additional details about the estimation procedures
and/or the calculation of the Coverage Rate*:
Coordinators: Marshall DeBerry, Charles Kindermann, and Mike Maltz
Note: These data are estimates which account for missing data and may differ from other published sources.
Please consult the file documentation for the 1996 file (abstract of ICPSR Study 2389) for definitions
and methods of imputation. The county-level UCR files which are the source of this information are
not official FBI UCR releases and are being provided for research purposes.
*The column labeled "Coverage Rate" refers to extent of actual data reported by a county's jurisdictions.
A Coverage Rate of .9 means that 90% of the data in that row are based on actual reports from agencies
representing 90% of the population in the county, the remaining 10% having been estimated
according to procedures developed by the FBI but are the responsibility of BJS.
There are separate Coverage Rates for arrest and offense data, since they are
provided to the FBI in separate reports from each jurisdiction.
Counties are arranged in order of their FIPS codes.
